IntroductionÂ¶

Our project aims to determine and analyze what makes a Student Successful through the application of Machine Learning Models. Students nowdays have so many different facets of life to balance, and we wanted to develop a model that could intake various features relevant to a student's performance, and determine whether or not a student will be considered successful from that data. Our work is important for the encouragment of students towards specific habits and goals that they should keep focus on to remain successful during their educational career! This tutorial allows for an easily accessible workflow from data cleaning to final interpretation, using a real life dataset from a professor and his roster of students!

Data Curation & PreprocessingÂ¶

Dataset:Â¶

https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/mahmoudelhemaly/students-grading-dataset

Our dataset is sourced off of Kaggle from a Professor, containing 5,000 records of real student data. It was specifically designed to explore patterns, correlations, and insights regarding academic performance, which makes it perfect for our tutorial! It features 20+ columns, with noteable ones including Total_Score, Extracurricular_Activities, Parent_Education_Level, and even Stress_Level.

Before anything else, first we must begin with importing some libraries so that we can effectively process our data! This project is done using Google Colab and the Python Language. One of our most important libraries for data processing is Pandas, which we will import below along with some mathmatical/statistical libraries (numpy, spicy.stats, statsmodels, sklearn) and data visualization libraries (matplotlib & seaborn)!

Now we need to determine how we will actually measure student performance. After discussion, we believe that student success should be calculated based on three main features: Total_Score, Stress_Level, and Sleep_Hours_per_Night. All three of these metrics encompass a students performance academically, mentally, and healthwise. We will combine these three features into a Success_Score that rewards high grades, low stress, and healthy sleep, and then perform our analysis against this metric, to determine what factors contribute to success, and eventually build a model that can predict such!

Exploratory Data AnalysisÂ¶

Since we have successfully completed our data curation, it's time for us to begin exploring our data and understanding connections, so that we can draw conclusions for our hypothesis.

We want to split our analysis into two distinct phases of testing: descriptive testing and modeling testing.
But first, we should address our missing values from before!

Analyzing Missing ValuesÂ¶

There is roughly 20% missing data for Parent_Education_Level. To quickly assess whether our data is MCAR (Missing Completely at Random) or MAR (Missing at Random), we can conduct a T test for numerical data and Chi-Squared Tests for categorical data. Both of these tests will produce a p value that quantifies how likely either is. If p value is > 0.05 then MCAR is plausible, but if it is below, it is statistically significant enough to consider MAR.

We can also use a heatmap to visualize if any of our t tests have especially low p values.

Learn more about missing values here!

Show/Hide Code â–¾
InÂ [Â ]:
df['miss_PE'] = df['Parent_Education_Level'].isna().astype(int)

numeric_cols = [
    'Age', 'Attendance_Pct', 'Midterm_Score', 'Final_Score',
    'Assignments_Avg', 'Quizzes_Avg', 'Participation_Score',
    'Projects_Score', 'Total_Score', 'Study_Hours_per_Week',
    'Stress_Level', 'Sleep_Hours_per_Night'
]
for col in numeric_cols:
    grp_obs = df.loc[df['miss_PE']==0, col].dropna()
    grp_miss = df.loc[df['miss_PE']==1, col].dropna()
    t_stat, p_val = ttest_ind(grp_obs, grp_miss, equal_var=False)
    print(f"{col:25} t-test p = {p_val:.3f}")


cat_cols = ['Gender', 'Department', 'Extracurricular_Activities', 'Internet_Access_at_Home']
for col in cat_cols:
    ct = pd.crosstab(df[col], df['miss_PE'])
    chi2, p_val, _, _ = chi2_contingency(ct)
    print(f"{col:25} chi2 p = {p_val:.3f}")

p_values = []
for col in numeric_cols:
    grp_obs = df.loc[df['miss_PE']==0, col].dropna()
    grp_miss = df.loc[df['miss_PE']==1, col].dropna()
    p = ttest_ind(grp_obs, grp_miss, equal_var=False).pvalue
    p_values.append(p)

#heatmap
pv_df = pd.DataFrame({'feature': numeric_cols, 'p_value': p_values})
pv_mat = pv_df.set_index('feature').T

plt.figure(figsize=(8,6))
sns.heatmap(
    pv_mat,
    annot=True,
    fmt='.3f',
    cmap='coolwarm_r',
    cbar=False
)
plt.title('T-test p-values: Missing vs. Observed Groups')
plt.yticks([])
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

Since our T test showed p = 0.008 for Participation_Score, we can not assume MCAR definitively. We should now run a formal MAR check using logistic regression to confirm this. Logistic regression will tell us if any of our other features can predict whether or not the parent education information is missing. If this is the case, then we must definitely rule out MCAR and conclude that Parent Education Level is MAR (Missing at Random).
Note that we are doing a univariate logistic regression test as Participation_Score is the only feature to have been remotely close to the threshold.

Learn more about Logistic Regression for Machine Learning here!

Show/Hide Code â–¾
InÂ [Â ]:
model = smf.logit(
    'miss_PE ~ Participation_Score',
    data=df
).fit(disp=False)
print(model.summary())

With the LLR p-value being 0.0099, the model with Prediction_Score predicts missingness extremely well. Because an observed variable significantly predicts missingness, we can conclude that Parent_Education_Level is Missing at Random. To fix this issue of MAR, we can consider imputation on Parent_Education_Level with respect to Participation_Score. Because we have not yet conducted Descriptive Testing to see how significant Parent_Education_Level is on our analysis, and because we only have one observed feature affecting our missing values, we will use Single Imputation for now. If we find that Parent_Education_Level is highly relevant to student success, we will revisit and consider Multiple Imputation. We can confirm successful imputation if we return a sum of 0 missing values, and move forward to descriptive testing!


Single Imputation is the method of finding the mode of a certain column and using that to fill in missing values. In this case, we will bin our data points into High and Low Participation_Scores, find the mode for each bins, and use those to impute on our missing values for Parent_Education_Level.
Show/Hide Code â–¾
InÂ [Â ]:
df['Part_High'] = df['Participation_Score'] >= df['Participation_Score'].median()

modes = df.groupby('Part_High')['Parent_Education_Level'] \
          .agg(lambda s: s.mode().iat[0])

df['Parent_Education_Level'] = (df['Parent_Education_Level'].fillna(df['Part_High'].map(modes)))

df.drop(columns='Part_High', inplace=True)
df.drop(columns='miss_PE', inplace=True)
df['Parent_Education_Level'].isna().sum()  # should be 0
Out[Â ]:
np.int64(0)

Descriptive Testing & VisualizationÂ¶

Now that our missing values have successfully been imputed on, it is time to begin Descriptive Testing! Descriptive testing is when we want to start exploring some of our features and their correlation to each other, so that we can decide which features are most related to analyzing student success. To do this, we will start by making a correlation matrix!


A correlation matrix is a compact way of visualizing every pairwise linear relationship among a set of numeric variables in a table. Its incredibly useful for EDA (Exploratory Data Analysis) because it allows for quick visualization of predictors that move together. It is also very useful for other applications such as Principal Component Analysis (PCA)!
Show/Hide Code â–¾
InÂ [Â ]:
numeric_df = df.select_dtypes(include=[np.number])

corr = numeric_df.corr()

    annot=True,
    fmt=".2f",
    linewidths=0.5,
)
plt.title("Correlation Matrix of Numeric Features")

Our correlation matrix proved extremely helpful! Now we have an understanding of which features hold meaningful correlation (>=0.3), in particular, Midterm, Total, and Project Score, along with Sleep_Hours_per_Night, all have high correlation to the Success_Score.
Before moving onto categorical variables, we should explore our numerical features first, especially now that we have concluded the importance of the features listed above. A quick bivariate numeric check we can do is a scatter plot matrix. A pairplot lets you eyeball non-linear trends, clusters, heteroskedasticity(spread of residuals) very quickly!

From the scatter plot, we can conclude visually that our highly correlated features all cluster in a semi-linear pattern against Success_Score.
Since we can conclude that the correlation follows a typical linear pattern, we can continue forward in our exploration with analyzing categorical features!
The easiest way to analyze our categorical features against a numerical feature is to use an ANOVA test!


An ANOVA test analyzes the variability between and withing groups, to see if those differences are statistically significant. This is done with using group means! Here we are doing a "multi-way" test, where we analyze the unique effect of each of our features, while accounting for the others!
Show/Hide Code â–¾
InÂ [Â ]:
dv   = 'Success_Score'
cats = ['Gender','Department','Extracurricular_Activities','Internet_Access_at_Home','Parent_Education_Level', 'Family_Income_Level']

formula = dv + ' ~ ' + ' + '.join(f'C({c})' for c in cats)

model       = ols(formula, data=df).fit()
anova_table = sm.stats.anova_lm(model, typ=2)   # Type II SS
print(anova_table)

fig, axes = plt.subplots(len(cat_cols), 1, figsize=(10, 20))

Model Testing & VisualizationÂ¶

For model testing, we want to choose between regression & classification. Since our Success_Score is numerical, we want to use regression, and since our pairplots showed linear trends in data, we can chose to begin our modeling with Linear Regression!
We're first going to just check the linear regression against the values we used to make the Success_Score


Linear Regression allows us to visualize the relationships between each factor and the Success Score, to conclude how much each feature contributes.

After visualizing linear regression on each of the factors, we can compare which hold more significant weight. Total score has the strongest relationship with success score, as each additional point in raw academic performance drives a substantial rise in Success Score.

Now we can construct a preliminary regression model. We choose our Independent Y (Success_Score) and Dependent Set X (everything else) to analyze how much each feature contributes to our independent set. We will be fitting an OLS (Ordinary Least Squares) to determine the set of coefficients that minimizes our residuals. It essentially allows us to see how each predictor shifts the outcome.
Whenever choosing to fit OLS, you want to inspect a few key features afterwards, specifically, Linearity (are there residuals or is it fitted), The Spread of Residuals, Normality and Colinearity. We will create diagnosis plots for these and interrpret the results according.


Note that we technically we already checked colinearity at the beginning with a correlation matrix, however true Multicolinearity involves Variance Inflation Factors, which measures how much variance inflates when you regress it on other predictors.
Show/Hide Code â–¾
InÂ [Â ]:
dv  = 'Success_Score'
num = ['Total_Score', 'Participation_Score', 'Attendance_Pct',
       'Study_Hours_per_Week', 'Projects_Score']
cats = ['Gender','Department','Extracurricular_Activities','Internet_Access_at_Home','Parent_Education_Level', 'Family_Income_Level']

formula = (dv + ' ~ ' + ' + '.join(num) + ' + ' + ' + '.join(f'C({c})' for c in cats))
model = ols(formula, data=df).fit()
print(model.summary())

def diagnostic_plots(model):
    exog          = model.model.exog
    exog_names    = model.model.exog_names
    vif_data = pd.DataFrame({
        "variable": exog_names,
        "VIF": [
            variance_inflation_factor(exog, i)
            for i in range(exog.shape[1])
        ]
    })
    print("\nVariance Inflation Factors\n", vif_data, "\n")

    fitted = model.fittedvalues
    resid  = model.resid

    fig, (ax1, ax2, ax3) = plt.subplots(1,3, figsize=(15,4))
    ax1.scatter(fitted, resid, alpha=0.3)
    ax1.axhline(0, color='red', linestyle='--')
    ax1.set_title('Fitted vs. Residuals')
    ax1.set_xlabel('Fitted values')
    ax1.set_ylabel('Residuals')

    ax2.hist(resid, bins=30, density=True, alpha=0.6)
    ax2.set_title('Residuals Histogram')

    sm.qqplot(resid, line='45', ax=ax3)
    ax3.set_title('Residuals QQ-Plot')

    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

diagnostic_plots(model)

                            OLS Regression Results                            
==============================================================================

Model Summary and ConclusionsÂ¶

From our OLS application, we can see that our R^2 value is 0.341, meaning that our predictors explain 34% of the variance in Success_Score. And our F-Statistic: 161.3 with a probability < 0.01, show that our predictors are highly significant in explaining the Success_Score.

As for key coefficients, our Total_Score coefficient of 0.14 is highly significant! It indicates that every one-point rise in total academic score â†’ +0.14 on Success_Score. Additionally, our Parent_Education_Level also has a modest impact, as students whose parents only completed high school, on average have a composite Success_Score that is 0.14 standard deviations lower than a student whose parents have higher education.

Diagnostics:Â¶

For Multicolinearity, we can see that all predictors fit between VIFs of 1.00 - 1.65. Most VIFs = 1 or < 2 are typically considered to have virtually no correlation to other X's, and are very safe. We can assume that all of our features have no concern of inflated variance or unstable coefficient estimates!

For Fitted vs Residuals, we have a consistent cloud shape from -3 to 3 across multiple fitted values, which is good because we typically want to avoid any type of special curve or pattern. This means we can conclude that our variance of errors is constant, and there is no need for a variance stabilizing transform.

For the Histogram, we usually aim for a traditional bell shaped curve centered at zero. In this case, we have a roughly symmetric curve, but with a less inconsistent tail. Although it visually maintains the shape we can conclude that residuals are close to normal, but we should stay aware of a few large errors in our dataset.

Finally, for the QQ plot of residuals (Normality), we typically aim for a tight attachment along the angle, however in this case we have tight attachment only in the middle, with the ends bending away. This indicates that we have some extreme residuals than a normal distribution, which aligns with our previous conclusion that we have slightly heavy tail behavior, which is a signal of a few extreme cases, but not of significant concern due to our large n of 5000.

Recap of Everything So Far!Â¶

Before we move further, lets quickly go over everything we've already done to understand our data.

Data PreprocessingÂ¶

We imported various libraries such as pandas, numpy, matplot, seaborn, spicy.stats, statsmodels, and sklearn.

We began parsing through turning raw text columns into native types, renamed â€œAttendance (%)â€ to Attendance_Pct and â€œStress_Level (1-10)â€ to Stress_Level, created miss_PE and Part_High as integer/boolean flags, binned participation into quartiles and later into a high/low Boolean for single-imputation and dropped ID, name and email columns

We also organized our data by cleaning the DataFrame, z-scoring three Success inputs, dropping extras, and creating a single Success_Score.

Basic Data Exploration & Summary StatisticsÂ¶

We utilized various Statistical Methods for:

  • Missing-data analysis (t-tests + Ï‡Â²) and visualization using heatmap & barplots for our Hypothesis test that Parent_Edu is MAR.
  • Correlation analysis (Pearson matrix + pairplot) and visualization with a scatter matrix for identifying top numeric predictors.
  • Categorical analysis (ANOVA + boxplots) and visualization with a multiway ANOVA table & boxplots for finding the categorical driver.
  • Simple regressions (regplots) + three red line scatterplots to determine our strongest linear predictor.
  • Full OLS model and diagnostics plus a summary table, VIFs, residual plots allowed for RÂ²/RÂ²adj, coefficient interpretations, and collinearity check.

    We reached many conclusions, a few of which being:

  • Participation_Score significantly predicts missing Parent_Education Level (pâ‰ˆ0.008), therefore it is Missing At Random (MAR).
  • Total_Score, Midterm, Project Score (râ‰ˆ0.6) & Sleep Hours (râ‰ˆ0.58) all correlate strongly with Success_Score.
  • OLS: every point in Total_Score adds ~0.14 to Success_Score, and having only High School educated parents knocks you down ~0.14 (all else equal).
  • ANOVA shows no significant categorical effects on Success_Score (all p>0.05).

    • Primary Analysis & VisualizationÂ¶

    Now that we have finished exploring our data, it is time to being our primary analysis! Before we begin applying models to our data, the first thing we need to is form a hypothesis.

    Based on our findings, we can assume the best model for our dataset would be Random Forest. Random Forest is a Machine Learning Model that is typically used when we have multiple categorical and numeric features. However, our previous conclusion showed us our categorical features are irrelevant to our analysis, therefore we are only going to be using our numerical features to train and test our model. We still believe Random Forest will be the best because its robust to overfitting and help us capture nonlinear relationships and more complex patterns. It still typically has the best performance compared to other models when working on real datasests that have been cleaned out and only contain numerical features.

    To test our hypothesis, we will be comparing Random Forest with other models that both tend to perform well on numerical data and are common models we have gone over in class. For this comparison, we will be using Decision Tree and Support Vector Regression

    Models such as K-nearest neigbor and K-means clustering would not work due to them being unsupervised machine learning models whereas our data has labels which we would want to use superivised algorithms to predict the success score of new students.

    Note: we included Support Vector Regression (SVR) in the dictionary which was not covered much in the material since its good for predicting continuos variables and might work well with our data.

    Before we begin appling models to our data, we need to scale and split our data before training. This ensures effective results in two ways: 1) scaled data allows for more consistent results across our models and 2) splitting data ensures that we can measure performance data that was not involved in training, for a more accurate assessment. Here we can quickly scale and split our data using the sklearn library's StandardScaler() and train_test_split() functions.

    Learn more about train_test_split here!

    Show/Hide Code â–¾
    InÂ [Â ]:
    test_size = 0.2
seed = 42

X = df[['Total_Score', 'Midterm_Score', 'Final_Score', 'Assignments_Avg', 'Quizzes_Avg', 'Participation_Score', 'Stress_Level', 'Attendance_Pct', 'Study_Hours_per_Week', 'Projects_Score', 'Sleep_Hours_per_Night']]
Y = df['Success_Score']

scaler = StandardScaler()

X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, Y, test_size=test_size, random_state=seed)
X_train_scaled = scaler.fit_transform(X_train)
X_test_scaled = scaler.fit_transform(X_test)

    Now that we have split our data, we want to introduce folds. This is essentially a cross validation technique where we split our data into distinct folds, fit the model on each train fold, evaluate it on a corresponding test fold, and receive a metric of the cross-validated accuracy. This encourages stability, fair comparison and helps prevent overfitting on our model, and is essential for compaing multiple models in a reproducible and unbiased manner!

    Learn more about k-fold here!

    Show/Hide Code â–¾
    InÂ [Â ]:
    kfolds = 5

kf = KFold(n_splits=kfolds, shuffle=True, random_state=seed)
for model_name, model in models.items():
  np.random.seed(42)
  cv = kf
  scoring = 'r2'
  print(f"Model: {model_name}")

  cv_scores = cross_val_score(model, X_train_scaled, y_train, cv=cv, scoring=scoring, error_score='raise')

  print(f"Cross-validated Accuracy: {cv_scores.mean()} (+/- {cv_scores.std()}) \n")

    Insights & ConclusionsÂ¶

    Finally, it is time to begin reviewing all of our analysis and discuss our conclusions!

    In our analysis, we set out to predict student success using three machine learning algorithms: Support Vector Regression (SVR), Decision Tree Regression, and Random Forest. We then used Linear Regression to compare all of them as this is a regression model with a linear pattern, as we initially believed that linear regression would be the highest due to our dataset's nature and construction of the Success_Score metric, making it the perfect comparison. Based on our prior experience and hypothesis, we expected Random Forest to outperform the other models due to its capability with handling larger datasets, robustness against overfitting and overall ability to capture complex feature interactions. Although random forest is known for its accuracy in utilizing both numerical and categorical features, our categorical features proved to be irrelevant in our data (shown in correlation matrix), so we removed this factor but still hypothesized Random Forest to retain the best accuracy due to its heavy use in real life numerical datasets.

    However, after training and evaluating all models, our results tell a different story. Surprisingly, Random Forest did not outperform the other two algorithms. While it performed well and showed high predictive capability, it was ultimately outclassed by both Support Vector Regression and Linear Regression. The Random Forest model retained strong accuracy, but it fell short in terms of minimizing prediction error (MSE), due to a higher value, and explaining the variance in our data (RÂ²), due to underperforming against SVR.

    Despite Linear Regression's lead in accuracy, SVR slightly surpassed it when comparing the RÂ² and Mean Squared Error (MSE) metrics. SVR achieved the highest RÂ² value (0.995) and the lowest MSE (0.017), indicating it was slightly better at minimizing error and explaining the variance in the data, possibly because it can capture subtle non-linear patterns that linear regression may miss. Random Forest also performed well, with a strong RÂ² (0.992) and low MSE (0.025), but it did not exceed the performance of either SVR or Linear Regression. Decision Tree underperformed against all metrics, and was our least accurate model.

    Overall: Linear Regression provided the highest predictive accuracy, indicating that it was most reliable in predicting whether a student would be classified as â€œsuccessfulâ€, however, it did not perform as well in prediction of larger errors. SVR performed best in error-based metrics which shows that it is less likely to make large errors in predicting studentsâ€™ exact success scores, causing us to reject our initial hypothesis of Random Forest being our best model of the three. While Linear Regression still retains the highest accuracy as hypothesized, SVR's outperformance regarding error based metrics makes it the most accurate model overall for continuous predictions in our study.

    In real world practice, our model can be applied by schools, advisors, or academic support services to identify students who will perform less successfully. Schools may input current data, such as total academic score, reported sleeping habits, and stress levels into our model in order to make predictions about which students will perform well and which students will require special intervention or not. This can help the professor, counselor, and school better understand what the student needs in order to improve their chances of being successful.
